<!-- COVER -->
<div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12px;letter-spacing:0.18em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#3B6B4A;">Project Handoff &amp; Onboarding Guide</div>
<h1 style="font-family:'Spectral',serif;font-weight:600;font-size:34px;line-height:1.15;margin:10px 0 6px;color:#14211B;">Cross-Site-of-Action Structural Bioinformatics of Herbicide Resistance</h1>
<p style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.5;color:#4A554E;margin:0 0 18px;font-style:italic;">A plain-language guide to what this project is, how it works, what we found, and what is left to do — written so a collaborator from any background can follow it.</p>
<div style="display:flex;gap:24px;flex-wrap:wrap;font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12.5px;color:#5A6660;border-top:2px solid #DED9CD;border-bottom:2px solid #DED9CD;padding:12px 0;margin-bottom:22px;">
  <span><strong style="color:#24302A;">Repository:</strong> <a class="lnk" href="https://github.com/gzc0063-hub/herbicide-resistance-structural-bioinf" target="_blank">github.com/gzc0063-hub/herbicide-resistance-structural-bioinf</a></span>
  <span><strong style="color:#24302A;">Status:</strong> Phase 4 complete · manuscript prepared for <em>Pest Management Science</em> submission</span>
</div>

<!-- HOW TO READ / TL;DR -->
<div style="background:#F3F1EA;border:1px solid #E3DECF;border-radius:8px;padding:20px 24px;margin-bottom:26px;">
  <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:14px;letter-spacing:0.02em;color:#2E5540;margin-bottom:8px;">THE PROJECT IN ONE PARAGRAPH</div>
  <p style="margin:0;font-size:15.5px;line-height:1.6;">Weeds become resistant to herbicides. One important way this happens is a tiny change (a <em>mutation</em>) in the exact protein the herbicide is designed to attack. These proteins are usually studied one at a time. This project put <strong>seven</strong> of those protein targets on a single, consistent measuring stick to ask one question: <strong>when resistance mutations appear across completely unrelated targets, do they tend to land in the same kind of structural neighborhood?</strong> Using only public 3-D protein structures and standard, reproducible calculations, we found that the answer is yes — resistance positions sit much closer to the business end of the protein than chance would predict — and, more importantly, we built a shared framework that sorts those mutations into meaningful categories rather than just saying "near the active site."</p>
</div>

<!-- CONTENTS -->
<h2 style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:15px;letter-spacing:0.08em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#3B6B4A;border-top:2px solid #14211B;padding-top:10px;margin:0 0 12px;">Contents</h2>
