<!-- 1 -->
<h2 style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:#14211B;border-top:2px solid #14211B;padding-top:14px;margin:30px 0 10px;">1 · What this project is about</h2>
<p>Herbicides kill weeds by jamming a specific protein the plant needs to survive — often an <strong>enzyme</strong> (a protein that carries out a chemical reaction). Each herbicide "family" is built to hit a particular enzyme, called its <strong>site of action</strong> or <strong>target</strong>. Over time, weed populations evolve ways to survive. The most direct route is <strong>target-site resistance (TSR)</strong>: the plant's own target enzyme changes shape slightly — usually a single altered building block — so the herbicide no longer sticks well, while the enzyme still works well enough for the plant to live.</p>
<p>This project is a <strong>comparative structural-bioinformatics study</strong>. "Structural" means we work with the three-dimensional shapes of these proteins. "Bioinformatics" means we do it with data and computer analysis rather than lab experiments. "Comparative" is the key word: instead of studying one target enzyme in isolation, we compared resistance mutations <em>across seven unrelated targets at once</em>, using the exact same measurements for each, so the families can finally be put side by side.</p>
<p>Concretely, for every confirmed resistance mutation we asked three simple questions about <em>where</em> that mutation sits in the protein: How close is it to the part that binds the herbicide? How exposed is it to the surrounding water? And how unchanged (conserved) is that position across many related species? Then we tested whether the pattern we saw could just be chance.</p>

<!-- 2 -->
<h2 style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:#14211B;border-top:2px solid #14211B;padding-top:14px;margin:30px 0 10px;">2 · Why it matters</h2>
<p>Two facts make this urgent. First, almost no genuinely new herbicide mechanisms have reached the market in decades — the chemical toolbox is not being refilled. Second, resistance keeps spreading; every major herbicide class now has resistant weed populations somewhere in the world. When a resistance mutation spreads through a field, an entire chemistry can stop working on that farm.</p>
<p>Understanding resistance at the structural level helps on both sides of the problem: it helps <strong>diagnose and predict</strong> which mutations are dangerous, and it informs the <strong>design of new herbicides</strong> that are harder to escape. This project contributes a shared, reproducible way to read the structural "signature" of resistance across many targets at once.</p>

<!-- 3 GLOSSARY -->
<h2 style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:#14211B;border-top:2px solid #14211B;padding-top:14px;margin:30px 0 10px;">3 · Glossary — every term in plain English</h2>
<p style="margin-bottom:14px;color:#4A554E;">Keep this handy; the rest of the document uses these words freely.</p>
<div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:0;border:1px solid #E3DECF;border-radius:8px;overflow:hidden;">
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Enzyme</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A protein that speeds up a specific chemical reaction the plant needs. Herbicide targets are usually enzymes.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Site of action / target</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">The specific enzyme a herbicide is designed to block.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Active site</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">The pocket on the enzyme where its chemistry happens — and usually where the herbicide binds. We call the innermost binding residues the <em>active-site core</em>.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Residue</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">One amino-acid building block in a protein chain. Proteins are chains of hundreds of residues, each numbered by position.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Mutation</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A change to a residue. E.g. <code class="p">Pro197Ala</code> means "position 197 changed from proline to alanine." A deletion (e.g. <code class="p">ΔG210</code>) removes a residue entirely.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Target-site resistance (TSR)</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">Resistance caused by a mutation in the target enzyme itself. Our focus.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Non-target-site resistance (NTSR)</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">Resistance from everything else the plant does — breaking the herbicide down, keeping it out, or making extra enzyme. Not studied here.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">PDB structure</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A 3-D model of a protein solved by experiment, stored in the public Protein Data Bank with a 4-character ID (e.g. <code class="p">1SEZ</code>).</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Homology model</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A computed 3-D structure for a protein we lack a solved structure for, built using a related protein as a template. Less certain than a solved structure.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Ligand</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A small molecule bound in the pocket — here, the herbicide, the natural substrate, or a metal ion. "Ligand-bound" structures show us exactly where the pocket is.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Distance-to-core percentile</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">How close a residue is to the active-site core, ranked against every other residue in the same protein. <strong>Low = close.</strong> Using a rank lets big and small proteins be compared fairly.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">SASA / RSA</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">Solvent-accessible surface area = how much of a residue is exposed to surrounding water. RSA is that value normalized by residue type, so residues can be compared on a 0–1 "how exposed" scale.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Conservation</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">How unchanged a position is across many species. Highly conserved positions are usually structurally or functionally important. Measured here with <em>Shannon entropy</em> (low entropy = highly conserved).</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Multiple sequence alignment</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">Lining up the same protein from many species so each position can be compared. Done here with the tool MAFFT.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Permutation test</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A way to ask "could this be chance?" We compare the real mutations against thousands of random sets of residues and count how often chance does as well.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">p-value</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">The fraction of random trials that matched or beat the real result. Small (e.g. p &lt; 0.001) means "very unlikely to be chance."</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Engineered vs. weed-evolved</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A mutation is <strong>weed-evolved</strong> if it was found in a real field population under real herbicide selection pressure. It is <strong>engineered</strong> (or lab-selected) if a scientist made it on purpose — by site-directed mutagenesis guided by computer docking, or by chemically mutagenizing seeds (EMS) and screening for survivors. Both are real science, but they are not the same evidence: this project never pools an engineered or lab-selected mutation into its main statistical test as if it had evolved in a weed. This is exactly why Gly101Ala (engineered/transgenic only) was excluded from EPSPS while Thr102Ile (found in a real resistant field population) was included.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">TIPS double mutation</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">Short for Thr102Ile + Pro106Ser: two EPSPS changes that occur together on the same gene copy in some glyphosate-resistant <em>Eleusine indica</em> (goosegrass) plants. Thr102Ile alone has never been found in nature and is thought to be too costly to the plant on its own &mdash; it only works, and only appears, paired with Pro106Ser.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Biophysical perturbation score</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">A simple, three-part measure of how physically different the mutant amino acid is from the original one: how much bigger or smaller it is (bulkiness), how much its water-loving/water-repelling character changes (hydropathy), and whether it gains or loses an electrical charge. Computed from published look-up tables, not a laboratory measurement &mdash; it is a lightweight stand-in for a full physics-based energy calculation (which would need licensed software this project does not have), reported honestly as that stand-in rather than as the real thing.</div></div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px 1fr;"><div style="background:#F3F1EA;padding:11px 16px;font-weight:600;">Global combined permutation test</div><div style="padding:11px 16px;">The same permutation-test idea (compare real positions to random ones), but run once on every family's accepted positions pooled together, instead of separately per family. Gives one overall number instead of four separate ones. It is simpler than a true mixed-effects statistical model (see Section 9, Result 3) but was the best cross-family test buildable without an R installation.</div></div>
</div>

<!-- 4 -->
<h2 style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:#14211B;border-top:2px solid #14211B;padding-top:14px;margin:30px 0 10px;">4 · Is it unique? What is new here</h2>
<p>Yes — in a specific, honest way. Plenty of excellent work exists on individual targets. What had <em>not</em> been done is a single, reproducible framework that measures resistance positions the same way across many unrelated targets and then tests the pattern statistically. Our contribution has three parts:</p>
<ul style="margin:6px 0 10px;padding-left:22px;line-height:1.7;">
  <li><strong>One shared yardstick.</strong> The same three metrics and the same statistical test are applied identically to PPO, ALS/AHAS, ACCase, and EPSPS, so the families can be compared directly for the first time.</li>
  <li><strong>A test that survives the obvious objection.</strong> A skeptic can say "of course resistance mutations are near the active site — that's almost the definition." So we re-ran the test with all direct-contact residues removed, and the enrichment held. That is the non-trivial result.</li>
  <li><strong>A typology, not just a headline.</strong> The real product is a reproducible way to sort each mutation by <em>how</em> it relates to the pocket — direct contact, adjacent, second-shell, allosteric hinge, or dimer-interface — which is far more useful than "it's near the active site."</li>
</ul>
<p>We are deliberate about what is <em>expected</em> versus <em>new</em>. That resistance mutations cluster near the active site is the expected baseline — after a hard internal review, the paper now <strong>leads with the typology</strong> as its central contribution and treats the proximity enrichment as the expected control, not the headline. The framework, the surviving-after-removal test, and the typology are the genuinely new parts.</p>

<!-- 5 TARGET FAMILIES -->
<h2 style="font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:22px;color:#14211B;border-top:2px solid #14211B;padding-top:14px;margin:30px 0 10px;">5 · The seven target families</h2>
<p>Four families form the fully-validated core of the analysis. HPPD is kept as a deliberate contrast (a "negative control"). FAT and DHODH are on the future roadmap. Each links to its live 3-D model in the Protein Data Bank.</p>
<table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:13.5px;margin:8px 0 6px;">
  <thead><tr style="background:#14211B;color:#F4F1EA;font-family:'IBM Plex Sans',sans-serif;text-align:left;">
    <th style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">Family</th><th style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">What the enzyme does</th><th style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">Role here</th><th style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">3-D model</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><td style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">PPO</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Protoporphyrinogen oxidase — chlorophyll/heme synthesis</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Pilot family (validated first)</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;"><a class="lnk" href="https://www.rcsb.org/3d-view/1SEZ" target="_blank">1SEZ</a></td></tr>
    <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;background:#FBFAF6;"><td style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">ALS/AHAS</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Acetohydroxyacid synthase — branched-chain amino acids</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Pooled core family</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;"><a class="lnk" href="https://www.rcsb.org/3d-view/1Z8N" target="_blank">1Z8N</a></td></tr>
    <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;"><td style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">ACCase</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Acetyl-CoA carboxylase — fatty-acid synthesis (CT domain)</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Pooled core (homology model)</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;"><a class="lnk" href="https://www.rcsb.org/3d-view/1UYS" target="_blank">1UYS</a></td></tr>
    <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #EDE9DE;background:#FBFAF6;"><td style="padding:9px 12px;font-weight:600;">EPSPS</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Shikimate pathway — the glyphosate target</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;">Pooled, two positions (updated 2026-07-07)</td><td style="padding:9px 12px;"><a class="lnk" href="https://www.rcsb.org/3d-view/8UMJ" target="_blank">8UMJ</a></td></tr>
